{"/service/ndnp/scu/batch_scu_dragonfruit_ver01/data/sn87065702/00516991148/1921032401/0186.xml":{"full_text":"J. FULLER LYON\nA\u00bb AppracUttM by J. B Traywtcb.\nIt wa* in the autumn of 1869 that\nI spent a night in the home of J. Ful\nler Lyon. It wai soon after hi* first\nmarriage. Ilia mother had died n few\nyear* before. They were living in\nthe old home, the place of hia birth,\nApril I, 1842. near Asbury church, in\nAbbeville county, a community of\nhigh ideal* and fine Christian homes.\nI had met brother Lyon ft a short\nwhile before, but that evening spent\nin that refined home with its delight\nful inmates ha* ever been a precious\nmemory to me. A few years after\nthis I became the pastor of the fam\nily. ft was the memorable year of\n1876, and he was that year elected\nProbate Judge of Abbevi(le county.\nSince then for forty four year* I have\nbeen in touch with him in church\nwork at district and annual confer\nences as co-worker and confidential\nfriend. He was treasurer of our\nBoard of Finance for nearly forty\nyears and his going away leaves a\nvoid in my life which can only be\nfilled in the great beyond.\nHe was by nature possessed of\nwhat is called personal magnetism,\nhandsome in jierson, courteous to all.\nendowed with a strong, clear mind\nand ready wit. a man of high ideals,\nclean speech and withal a warm\nhearted. deeply spiritual Christian.\nHis love and loyalty to the church\nknew no abatement. His long and\nirtiwiiui service cnunn was\nonly the isj\u00bbuc of fruitage \u00abf the fine\nold Methodist homo in which ho grew\nup. And then his own homo was over\nan inspiration to d<> and ho the best.\nMs* first wife, the mother of hi*\ntwo sons. Win. Andrew Lyon of Au\ngusta, (in., and J. Fraser Lyon of Cr*\nlumhia, S. was n most splendid\nChristian woman. Her whole life\nwas for the highest and host. After\nher death in 1894 he married Mrs.\nI\u2019pehurch of North Carolina. She did\nnot live long. About twelve years\naco he married Mis* Jo Langford of\nProsperity. 8. C. This has been most\nfortunate, for she has been every\nthing that a good wife could he. He\nginning with the year 1877 Judge\nLyon held the office of Probate Judge\nfor Abbeville county for eighteen\nyears, ami for the last twenty year*\nhe has been bond clerk in the State\nTreasurer\u2019s office. In all his life as\na civil offlv er he carried into the of\ntier his fine courteous spirit. Faithful\nand efficient, he honored the office\nfur more than the other honored him.\nAs a soldier our State never fur\nntshed a more gallant and truly hrave\nman. He volunteered at the out\nbreak of the War Between the States,\nfirst in thr Army of Virginia, fight\ning in the battle of Manassas; was re\ntired rally in 1 H<52 because of til\nhealth, but when this was regained he\nwent back into service in the West\nern army, fought in all the battles\nfrom Murfreesboro to Atlanta. At\nK*ra church, near Atlanta, he was so\nseriously wou .dcd it became neces\nsary to amputate his left arm. When\nwell again he started back into ser\nvice, hut the surrender came and he\nsaw no more service. He never lost\ninterest in the memories of that great\nstruggle. He was greatly lo-ved by\nthe Confederate veteran*. He wa*\nhonored by them ao much at hi* death\nhe held the rank of brigadier (feneral\nof the veteran* and hi* body wa*\nburied in a Confederate uniform.\nBrother Lyon had a seriou* fall\nla*t August. His loved one* watched\nover him between hope and despair,\nbut hi* age and the *enousnr\u00bb* of the\nfall proved too much for hi* *trentrth.\nSo, on November 5, he went away,\ndying at the home of hi* son, Hon. J.\nFra*er Lyon, in Columbia. S. C. Al\nthough hi* pain was great, a* the end\ncame, *o quietly did he fall asleep\nit wa* like a babe sweetly resting on\nmother\u2019* brea*t. Hi* remain* were\ncarried back to Abbeville, accompa\nnied by hi* family and a large num\nber of friends, and were laid to rent\nin .ueirone cemetery. Hrothrr Lyon\nha* run*- from us, He hail almost\nruchej the four sror^ limit, in a\nRood old age. This is a better world\nbecause Fuller Lyon lived in it. As\nwe look on hi* well rounded life, his\ncheerful spirit, his life of service, his\ntriumphant faith and hope, it gives u*\nmore faith in humanity. My dear\nfriend is gone. I bid him farewell. I\nknow 1 shall greet him in the morning.\nWHY THF. FINANCIAL APPEAL\nAT THIS TIME?\nBy John S. Chadwick.\nWhen the General Conference\nspoke in 1918 it was a real venture\nof faith. The nation a as at war. and\n<n su-h a world struggle it appearrd\nthen would end only in world bank\nrujitry. In May 191H we did not aee\nvictory by faith. We believes! that\nAmerica would eome out of the\nstruggle with *u. h a burden of debt\nas would delay for years the return\nof prosperity to the nation. And\neven with that financial burden upon\nus for a generation and more, we\nsaw America giving herself in iwr\nvies- to a world\u2019s needs. In a day\nsuch a* this can the Church surrender\nideals that moved us in 1918 to\npledge the faith of the nation and of\nMethodism to sarnlicial service?\nWe must compare ourselves with\nourselves in 1918 and not with our\nselves m 1920. Our ftnan\u00ab-ia! situ\nation is not a favorable one, but,\nwith two jears of unparatlelled pros\npertly, are we not in better condi\ntion than three years ago\nOur schools nave jttotx! dur*\ni\u00bbij{ the years of prosperity. How\nthey have lived and have served so\nwell the thousands who have rumr\nto them only the men and women\nwho have carried the heavy burden*\nfor a r h chur\u00bb h will ever know,\n('an we atTord to *end them into an\nother scholastic year with no definite\npledye of the Church\u2019* help.\nAn extension of the time for the\nfinancial appeal means an additional\nevper.se such a* our schools can ill\nafford to bear.\nThis is no day for the Church to\njoin forces with those who ery cal\namity; no time for the Church to be\na prophet of evil. Prosperity and\nstable business conditions will come\nthrough the people wh>, in the day\nof adversity, aee the better day\nahead the people who hearten human\nity by deeds well u word*. The\nChurch must not fail the nation in\nit* time of need.\nThe considerations named, and\nothers, were factors in determining\na policy for the Church. But one\nthat in the thought of our leaders\nha* had first is\u2014The future life and\nservice of our Methodism is in the\nissues of the Christian Education\nMovement. It s a matter so vital\nthat there can be but one thought\nand purpose in the mind and soul of\nSouthern Methodism\u2014it must be\ncarried through. For an issue such\nas this our help is in God. He was\nwith us when we declared our pur\npose to attempt and to carry through\nthis enterprise. He wit! not fail us\nnow. Whether or not we have willed\nthat it be thus, we have come to a\nday where we must prove our loyalty\nto the ideals of the Master. We\ncan better prove it in a time such\nas this.\nThe financial objectives of the\nChristian Education Movement have\nbeen in the minds of our people for\nmany months. We now know the\ntime appointed for the response by\nSouthern Methodists to this call.\nCnti! now we have considered the\nfinancial objectives in the light of\nbusiness conditions throughout the\nnation. It is our duty from now to\nface that question in the iight of\nour obligations to the kingdom and\nto one who rules in that Kingdom.\nAnd it is our privilege to be of that\ncompany of Methodists who shall\nhave a share in the carrying through\nof the greatest enterprise our Church\nhas undertaken?\nWE ARE NOT RESPONSIBLE FOR\nRESULTS.\nMost of us spend a lot of time fret\nting and worrying over result*. We\nare conscious of the fart that we have\ndone our beat, but the results are not\nsatisfactory and we, therefore, pro\nceed to bring accusations against\nourselves.\nIf there is one thing that is taught\nclearly in God\u2019s word, it is that if\nyou and I do our duty, God will take\ncare of the results.\nThank God, our finite heads and\nhearts and hands are not responsible\nfor the final outcome, if we do our\nbest.\nWith God, faithfulness is the one\nand only test.\nIf God held you and roe responsible\nfor results we would have a right to\naccuse Him of injustice, for the fu\nture is in His hand with all its at\ntendant consequences. In that realm\nthe Infinite is supreme and the finite\nis absolutely without power or re\nsponsibility.\nMine is the duty to remain faith\nful. The responsibility for results is\nGod\u2019s. C. C. FeathersUme.\nVYN\u00abm\u00bb 4f)\u00abte?\nDear Subscriber: Kindly read the date-label of\nyour Advocate and renew if your subscription is out or\nnearly so.\nYou are cmly one but you are one.\nIf all of our friends will only rally to our aid, one\nwill become a thousand.\nIf they do not our burden is correspondingly heavy.\nWe are trying to give you a good paper. We cannot\nsucceed without your help.\nSouthern Christian Advocate.\n4\nCut This Out\nPaste on Your Memory Or Mail to Us\nHerewith find $2.00 for one year\u2019s subscription\nto the Southern Christian Advocate.\nMy pastor\u2019s name is Rev_\nIs this a Renewal? An*_\nOr a New subscription? Ans_\nName___\n(fctirn nam* a* it on tmr H\u00bbtt\nStreet or Route_____\nP. O.___\nIf your aatno it ioeorroct tt our litl, or if you art gutting\n*wo or if your popor it aol coait| rofnUrty, idvut ut.\n4\n4\n4\n4\n\n\n\n\nt\n\n\n\nt\n\nt\n\ni\n\n\n\n\n\ni\ni","height":"17184","width":"13120"}}
